 Users who access both Grok and X without a linked sign-in could be counted twice.\n- The metric also only captures *registered* users, meaning it excludes unregistered or anonymous visitors, but the direction of the acknowledged error is upward (overcounting), not downward.\n- The company itself directs investors to treat the figure as an **estimate**, not a precise measurement—unusual language for a headline KPI in an S-1 prospectus.\n\n#### b) Daily Posts Inflation by AI-Generated Content\n- The explicit admission that daily posts "may include posts generated by AI or accounts managed by AI" means this metric **does not represent a pure measure of organic human engagement or discourse**. A potentially material (but undisclosed) portion of the ~350 million daily posts is artificially generated.\n- This is particularly significant given the scale of AI-generated content on the platform: the filing separately discloses that Grok\'s image and video generation system produced approximately **10 billion images and over 2 billion videos per month** on average for the quarter ending March 31, 2026.\n- The filing does not quantify what percentage of daily posts are AI-generated, leaving investors unable to disaggregate human from machine activity.\n\n#### c) Compounding Effect on Downstream Metrics\n- The filing notes that X\'s "real-time engagement feedback" is used to optimize ad delivery via the X Ads Manager. If AI-generated posts and AI-managed accounts inflate engagement signals, **advertising performance metrics (impressions, clicks, conversions) may also be distorted**, potentially undermining advertiser trust and the platform\'s monetization model.\n- The filing does not explicitly address how AI-managed accounts might skew advertising performance metrics—a notable disclosure gap.\n\n#### d) Strategic Deprioritization of MAU\n- The filing further discloses that management is focused on revenue and operating margins and manages the business to drive profitability **"rather than with the primary objective of growing or maintaining MAU levels."** This signals that MAU may decline or stagnate without management viewing it as a primary concern, reducing its utility as a forward-looking indicator.\n\n#### e) Data Quality and "Data Poisoning" Risk\n- The filing warns that Grok has been alleged to be susceptible to **"data poisoning"**—where malicious actors intentionally corrupt training data to manipulate model behavior. If AI-generated posts constitute a meaningful share of the content that feeds back into model training, the reliability of both the engagement metrics *and* the AI models themselves could be compromised in a self-reinforcing cycle.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| Metric | Caveat | Core Implication |\n|---|---|---|\n| **MAU (~550M)** | Deduplication "may not fully capture all instances of duplication"; should be "viewed as an estimate" | Likely overstates unique human users; not a precise KPI |\n| **Daily Posts (~350M)** | "May include posts generated by AI or accounts managed by AI" | Does not measure organic human engagement; AI inflation is unquantified |\n\nTogether, these caveats imply that the filing\'s headline AI engagement metrics are **not fully reliable as measures of genuine human activity**. Investors cannot determine the true organic user base or the true volume of human-generated content, which limits the interpretability of these metrics for valuation, growth benchmarking, or advertising-revenue modeling. The absence of quantified breakdowns (e.g., AI vs. human post share, or deduplication error rates) represents a material disclosure gap.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Filing (Filed May 20, 2026) — Glossary definitions of MAU and Daily Posts; Risk Factors regarding AI engagement metrics, data quality, and data poisoning"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
